      "text": "Here at The Syllabus we feel the weight of history. After 100 editions, we will soon be publishing our 100,000th piece – our [https://cabinet.the-syllabus.com/archive/?size=n_30_n archive] reflects some tectonic changes in the topics we track. So, to celebrate these milestones, we’re dusting off our stacks, and looking back on two years of curated syllabi.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "66edd71dcb832ea4",
      "text": "***\n\n\nIn *The Activist*, we have featured articles on how ‘the reactionary worldview of far-right civilizationism’ [https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0896920519894051 represents] ‘an alternative elite grand strategy’ for the present period of structural crisis, and others explaining how ‘a duopoly of the centre-left and centre-right political establishment’ [https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/1467-923X.12765 facilitated] the political emergency by taking issues like immigration and inequality off the public agenda.\n\n\n\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "d63eda3cf59d1d3c",
      "text": "We also saw that, in some places in the Global South, like Indonesia, the hierarchical identity politics of masculinity can be [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/07256868.2019.1675612 traced] back to their colonizers. And that colonialism lives on even in New York City, where white entrepreneurs [https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/full/10.1177/0308518X19886321 attract] Airbnb guests by marketing majority-Black neighbourhoods as consumable experiences. The conquests are ‘no longer over gold and ivory, but over sandwiches at a local bodega’.\n"
