        "text": "The pendulum is also swinging on the historical side: critics say that it was societal developments, not climatic factors, that finally [https://muse.jhu.edu/article/742859/summary caused] Rome to fall. At least there is some consensus on how the apocalypse will look: deep in the desert, the spectacular legacy of Biosphere 2 still [https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0016718521001524 sells] techno-centric ‘solutions’ to ecological dilemmas.\n\n\n\nWhen science and society are at odds, the Frankfurt School remains a good place to turn. Adorno’s take on the fascistic tendencies of the mid-century American – that ‘formally free individual who takes pleasure in lies that sound like truth’ – fits the climate science denier, too. Benjamin’s writings on Schuld, both guilt and debt at once, refocus the problem of fossil capital into the necessity of a climate strike. And if the accelerationist in you proves hard to ignore, try reflecting with Epimetheus on the ‘unintended consequences and accumulated errors’ that produced the Anthropocene in the first place.\n\n\n***\n\n\nSince our first edition, heterodox economic thinking has flourished. In The Progressive, we have featured articles calling out the ‘gaping silence’ in mainstream economics, which ignores how capitalism reproduces inequality along racial lines. This was not the only case for revamping the curriculum: to teach Econ 101 as usual is to ‘provide succor for the maintenance of the status quo’.\n\n\n\nAs an alternative, leftist discourses of post-work have grown popular, but the stories they tell about business models, technologies, and labour markets may turn out to be empirically unsustainable. On the question of proof, the Austrian School is instructive: it, too, rejected dominant paradigms in search of a framework for its ideological position, since socialism after Lange could only be contested on political terms, ‘by those whose economic interests it opposes’.\n\n\n\nMost macroeconomists, meanwhile, remain concerned with perfect, rather than real, competition. They take their imaginary assumptions back to the drawing board, never accepting deviations as inherent features of market economies. To try to account for all this confusion, some have looked to how past academic debates breached the public sphere, starting with Galbraith and Friedman's TV programmes, broadcast after stagflation discredited mainstream theory. Conservatives have lately tried to appropriate these same mechanisms to saturate our economic thought.\n\n\n***\n\n\nThe news from across the globe has also been fraught, as captured in The Cosmopolitan. First was Brexit, which, in the end, ‘will do little to alter the current dominance of a neoliberal market-led ideology’ over EU employment and social policy. This same ideology has found Kafkaesque expressions wherever it appears: in the United States, prisons are striving for sustainability by producing ‘green prisoners’ – those incarcerated individuals ‘willing to take responsibility for their rehabilitation and diminish their economically burdensome behaviors’.\n\n\n\nWe heard too much from this country, as Trump, only halfway through his term, had already ‘removed a number of obstacles to pursue a unilateral foreign policy placing America first’. And even if the social media bans do punctuate Trump’s denouement, we have reason to doubt tech-deterministic accounts of the public sphere; Twitter can’t shoulder all the blame for ‘ “post-truth” politics’. Nor is the US the only empire still haunting the Middle East; the UK treated Afghanistan like a laboratory, too. We caution our readers that ‘portrayals of the country as retrogressive elide the colonial violence that has ensured the very backwardness that is now considered Afghanistan’s enduring characteristic’.\n\n\n\nThat said, it is no paradox that the region has been another wellspring for radical imagination. Palestinian laughter, for instance, destabilises relations of power through its ‘refusal to normalize conditions of subjugation’. Other contributions reconstructed the revolution in Tunisia, underscoring the subversive role artists have to play in ‘sensing the next battle’.\n\n\n***\n\n\nAs for those who follow The Machinist to see how to stop Big Tech, take heed that the prevailing wisdom ‘rests on a bed of nonsense’ – at least when that wisdom begins from consumer welfare antitrust. And that, even more disheartening, the protection afforded to data subjects by the GDPR has had the double-edge of serving Google and Facebook: for them it is ‘a tool to harm rivals by restricting access to the data they need to compete in the digital advertising and ad tech industry’.\n\n\n\nSince our launch in 2019, the hype about AI has only grown; this cresting ‘wave of inflationary thinking leads to confusion and disorientation in a time when decision makers need moral clarity’. Those in power have been left to spend on alarming applications, none more lethal than autonomous weapons technologies, which, in a twist, may actually enhance terrorist tactics.\n\n\n\nOther trends solidified, too, especially concerning China: it has standardised 5G technologies abroad under the aegis of techno-nationalism; it has emerged as a fragile crux along the global semiconductor value chain; and it has begun regulating its national firms, making good on intentions stated many months ago. Also clear is that the West misses the full complexity of China’s social credit system, which reflects a unique understanding of the law as moral code.\n\n\n***\n\n\nWe thank you for letting The Syllabus be your guide to the digital public sphere.\n\n\n\nFrom Bilbao and Berlin,\n\n\nEkaitz Cancela & Marc Shkurovich\n\n\nHuman Editors Behind The Syllabus’s Algorithm\n\n\nThe Syllabus, 34 North 7th Street Brooklyn, New York, 11249\n\n"
